em" custom_margin="31px||8px|||" header_font_size_tablet="35px" header_font_size_phone="25px" header_font_size_last_edited="on|phone" global_colors_info="{}"]<h1><span>FOOD ALLERGENS</span></h1>[/et_pb_text][et_pb_text _builder_version="4.17.4" _module_preset="default" text_font="Dosis||||||||" text_text_color="#000000" text_font_size="16px" text_line_height="1.8em" global_colors_info="{}"]<p class="mbr-section-subtitle pb-3 mbr-fonts-style mbr-white align-left display-5" style="text-align: justify;">Many people who come across allergy problems rarely realise that some of the common food items such as milk, tomatoes, groundnut, curd or cabbage can cause allergy. We cannot know who is affected by what unless we take a test. Allergy test with blood samples are the ideal test as with a single sample we can conduct tests over a large range of items. Even a tiny amount of the allergy-causing food can trigger signs and symptoms such as digestive problems, hives or swollen airways. Food allergies are typically IgE-mediated, which means that the body produces large amounts of antibodies that specifically target the proteins of certain food products.</p>
